05060nam a22006975i 9780292734913DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212011txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927349137 a10.7560/7235972doi  a(DE-B1597)587199  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPN5449.T8bB76 2011eb 7aHIS0550002bisacsh04a079/.56109042221 aBrockett, Gavin D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHow Happy to Call Oneself a Turk :bProvincial Newspapers and the Negotiation of a Muslim National Identity /cGavin D. Brockett. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2011  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Imagining the Secular Nation: Mustafa Kemal and the Creation of Modern Turkey -- tChapter 2. Narrating the Nation: Print Culture and the Nationalist Historical Narrative -- tChapter 3. Provincial Newspapers and the Emergence of a National Print Culture -- tChapter 4. Religious Print Media and the National Print Culture -- tChapter 5. Muslim Turks against Russian Communists: The Turkish Nation in the Emerging Cold War World -- tChapter 6. Mustafa Kemal Atatürk and Mehmed the Conqueror: Negotiating a National Historical Narrative -- tChapter 7. Religious Reactionaries or Muslim Turks?: Print Culture and the Negotiation of National Identity -- tConclusion. A Muslim National Identity in Modern Turkey -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe modern nation-state of Turkey was established in 1923, but when and how did its citizens begin to identify themselves as Turks? Mustafa Kemal Atatürk, Turkey's founding president, is almost universally credited with creating a Turkish national identity through his revolutionary program to "secularize" the former heartland of the Ottoman Empire. Yet, despite Turkey's status as the lone secular state in the Muslim Middle East, religion remains a powerful force in Turkish society, and the country today is governed by a democratically elected political party with a distinctly religious (Islamist) orientation. In this history, Gavin D. Brockett takes a fresh look at the formation of Turkish national identity, focusing on the relationship between Islam and nationalism and the process through which a "religious national identity" emerged. Challenging the orthodoxy that Atatürk and the political elite imposed a sense of national identity from the top down, Brockett examines the social and political debates in provincial newspapers from around the country. He shows that the unprecedented expansion of print media in Turkey between 1945 and 1954, which followed the end of strict, single-party authoritarian government, created a forum in which ordinary people could inject popular religious identities into the new Turkish nationalism. Brockett makes a convincing case that it was this fruitful negotiation between secular nationalism and Islam—rather than the imposition of secularism alone—that created the modern Turkish national identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aIdentification (Religion)xPolitical aspectszTurkeyxHistoryy20th century. 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspectszTurkeyxHistoryy20th century. 0aMass mediaxSocial aspectszTurkeyxHistoryy20th century. 0aMuslimszTurkeyxHistoryy20th century. 0aNationalismzTurkeyxHistoryy20th century. 0aPrintingxPolitical aspectszTurkeyxHistoryy20th century. 0aPrintingxSocial aspectszTurkeyxHistoryy20th century. 0aTurkish newspapersxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Turkey & Ottoman Empire.2bisacsh40uhttps: